John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
The private schools in Scotland are known for the outstanding performance of their students and it has continued in 2018 with new, impressive test results, which are still reinforced by individual and group success in sports, arts, music and other social practices.
These schools have up to 30,000 students across Scotland, with The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) defending them, and they strive to provide their students and their parents with the best possible service.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further graduate studies, the careers they have chosen, and their status as global citizens.
As educators who can compile and teach custom curriculums, we see that new language continues to be a popular subject of study in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it touches his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, it touches his heart.”
This is an important reminder that we can’t just rely on English to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's test results show us that languages are at the top of the list with the highest proportion of students achieving exams in private schools.
68 percent of students who learned a foreign language received a grade of A.
The data, collected from 74 schools within SCIS, showed that 72 percent of students received a grade of A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French, and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish also received a grade of A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an essential qualification that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
At the moment, languages, as an elective, are placed in the same position as science-related subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in private school curriculums and elsewhere.
A 2014 poll conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that for the reasons employers gave that hiring was difficult, 17 percent was due to a lack of people with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future jobs.
Now that more and more jobs require proficiency in languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career people choose, they will have a real advantage in the future if they learn another language, but it is a skill that will last a lifetime.
The ability to interact directly with people from other countries will give a multi-talented person an automatic advantage over the competitors.
According to a poll conducted by YouGov on over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them could not speak another language well enough to sustain conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-letter percentile, or 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important for children today to immediately invest in language learning.
Multilingualism, especially in emerging markets, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, the language they teach varies between schools.
A certain number of schools will focus on classic novelties, while others will teach languages that are considered to be most important to the UK in the run-up to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter where your child's interest lies, they will always be able to choose from the languages of private schools with specially trained teachers.
Scottish private schools are committed to offering a learning environment, which will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied that at this time, in a global business environment, language continues to be essential for the country's future, and it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be viewed as "international skills in communication."
Private schools will continue to offer choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards is the chairman of the Scottish Private School Council.
