Harvard students take classes in sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University has provided all students with more sleep in an effort to resist the growing tendency of students to wake up and learn all night with the help of caffeine tablets.
A study found that students at the best universities in the world often know little or nothing when it comes to the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and the Women's Hospital, designed the course, believing it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea of doing the course after giving a lecture on the impact that sleep deprivation has on learning ability.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I being told this only now, in my senior year?’
She said that no one had told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he toldTelegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleeping habits help learning skills and performance in sports and even contribute to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the school's health services, said that the college had decided to introduce the course after finding out that students were extremely sleep-deprived over the week.
The course is an hour in length and includes a number of interactive projects.
One section features a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports can worsen with lack of sleep, along with the importance of good routine for sleep.
In the second part, participants are told how lack of sleep over the long term can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the school area with interactive symbols then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of the students.
But we feel they have a right to know this, just as one has a right to know of the health effects of smoking cigarettes," Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that favors those who stay awake and learn all night is still present, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep of good quality should be a "secret weapon" for students to ward off stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said – even to avoid fattening, because lack of sleep increases the brain's call for food so that the body is persistent.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical biology from California, helped Professor Czeisler put the course together, but he sat one of the professor's courses last year in his freshman year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to call for a course for all students in the school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all master students to complete a similar course before they start studying at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider adjusting an alarm clock, reminding them to go to sleep, and to wake them up, and bearing in mind the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can confuse the body's internal clock and lead to trouble falling asleep.
