Geiger developed a method for studying and measuring radioactivity, and that invention eventually led to a device called a Geiger meter.
The Geiger meter has gained a firm place in the scientific world since, but was also popular in pop culture, for example in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in unlikely roles as scientists:
Man: “What the hell is this?”
Rogers: “This is a Geiger probe, used to find radioactive materials such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on you can hear the effects of the atoms due to the radioactivity in the stones."
Evans: "It's really crashing right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
