The Man Who Invented the Internet Has Plans to Start a New Internet to Fight Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the man who invented the internet, is going to set up a seed company to fight Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The last project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on the Solid, open platform Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people are allowed to access what information.
In a private interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly stated that the intent behind Inrupt was "world domination."
“We have to do it now,” he said of the company.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses technology from Solid to enable people to create their own "personal data store online" or POD.
It includes a list of contacts, a to-do list, a calendar, a music collection, and other personal and work-related devices.
It is similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify all being present in one browser and all at the same time.
The unique thing about the personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user who can access any information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment using data."
According to John Bruce, CEO of the company, the idea of Inrupt is that the company provides the inputs, processes, and appropriate skills to help make Solid accessible to everyone.
Currently, the company consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers hired as contractors to work on the project, and a group of developers on a volunteer basis.
As of this week, technology developers around the world could create their own independent applications using the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team should not be in talks with "Facebook and Google about whether or not to initiate a complete change that would put their current business model on its head overnight.
“We don’t ask for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in an article published Saturday on Medium that Inrupt had it "a goal of creating energy in business and ecosystems that helps protect the honesty and quality of the new site based on Solid."
Berners-Lee revolutionized the Internet in 1994 when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over the neutrality of the network.
Berners-Lee will remain the founder and CEO of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation of the Open Data Institute, even while establishing Inrupt.
"I'm full of optimism for the next season of the network," added Berners-Lee.
