The latest warships of the German Navy should have been built in 2014 to replace old warships from the Cold War period, but it will not be ready until the first of next year due to broken systems and ever-increasing costs, according to news in the area.
The building of the "Rheinland-Pfalz," the lead ship of the brand new warships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to sources from a military spokesman who spoke to Die Zeit newspaper.
The ship had been due to be taken into service by the Navy in 2014, but serious problems after delivery plagued the project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 are to be replaced by the Bremen-class warships, which have come of age.
They should be equipped with a more powerful cannon, multiple anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and hiding techniques such as reduced radar, infrared, and sound signals.
Other important features are a longer period of use - it should be possible to use the latest ships for up to two years away from their home ports.
However, constant delays mean that these warships of the latest type – which are said to allow Germany to show its strength at sea – will be already obsolete when they are finally taken into use, says Die Zeit.
The F125 warship came to the news last year when the German army officially refused to take over the fleet, returning it to the Blohm & Voss slip in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy has returned a ship to the manufacturer after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind the split, but German media spoke of many women seriously "lack of software and hardware" that rendered the warship useless if sent to war.
Deficiencies in software were particularly important because a Baden-Wuerttemberg-class warship will be piloted by a crew of 120, which is half the size of a Bremen-class warship.
It was also found that the ship was far too heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to make additions to it in the future.
The 7,000-ton ship "Rheinland-Pfalz" is estimated to be twice the weight of a similar class ship used by the Germans in World War II.
Aside from hardware flaws, the cost of the entire project - including crew training - is starting to cause problems.
