The National Trust for the Conservation of Nature spies on the secret life of the bats
A new study, conducted on land in the Scottish Highlands, aims to find out how bats use the landscape when they hunt for food.
It is hoped that the results shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation efforts in the future.
The study, conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland, will monitor different species of bats in the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at key locations around the area to monitor the behavior of the bats over the period.
NHS staff and volunteers will also go on patrols with handheld sensors.
Experts will audio-detect all recordings to find out the frequency of the calls, which the bats emit, and what species do what.
Maps of habitats and reports will then be published to create an accurate picture of their behaviour on a geographical scale.
Rob Dewar, a wildlife conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results reveal what kind of habitats are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, e.g. by creating meadows and how best to maintain woodland for bats and other related species.
Bats have declined significantly in the last century in Scotland and throughout the UK.
They are at risk from construction and development projects that affect their nests and reduce habitat.
Windmills and lights can also pose risks, including flypaper and certain building materials treatments, as well as attacks from household pets.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their ears are much more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey, because they are used to fishing at night.
They used advanced echo detection technology to find insects and objects that are on their flight path.
NTS, responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important parks and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organization employs ten experts, who perform regular inspections, nest inspections, and sometimes rescue operations.
The association has even established Scotland's first and only batting grounds at the Threave ranch in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the manager of the ranch, says he is the perfect area for them.
"The area here at Threave is great for bats," he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of grown trees and lots of good habitats.
But there is still a lot of ignorance about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of checking with bats before any maintenance is carried out on a dwelling, as the possible unintentional destruction of one nest can kill up to 400 female bats and juveniles and completely destroy all bats in the area.
Bats are protected and it is forbidden to kill them, harass or disturb, or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish representative with the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot of unlearned bats and we don't know how well many of their species are doing."
