Why a trade war between the U.S. and China could be good for Beijing
The first shots of the trade war between the United States and China were arduous, and although the war is far from over, the gulf between the countries could be favorable for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump fired the first warning shot earlier this year by imposing a tax on China's main export products, including solar batteries, steel and aluminum.
The biggest rise came this week with new tariffs covering $200 billion worth of goods (150 billion pounds), and taxing as much as half of all goods imported into the United States from China.
