Latest news of algae blooms: concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest news from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in algae concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more severe algae blooms are reported in certain areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota Charlotte and Collier counties - suggesting decreasing concentrations.
The algae flower covers an approximately 200-mile shoreline from northern Pinellas to southern Lee County.
Individual flowers can be found about 10 miles (16 km) from Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
There have also been reports of algae blooms in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations at or near Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, extremely low to high concentrations in Manatee County, extremely low to high concentrations in or near the shores of Sarasota County, extremely low to moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, extremely low to high concentrations in or near the shores of Leesota County.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
